as covered previously in the previous pages, we talked about how data travels across multiple LANs using the help of routers - devices with built-in routing tables responsible with the daunting task of sending and receiving packets between different networks, while said networks are distinguished from each other with network IDs, set by IP addresses and how a network is configured. as we discussed, the method of information interconnection between multiple LANs is done via default gateways where devices which request data from another LAN use a router, or the default gateway in the network, as the primary tool for gathering data from other networks. however, a very common problem which rises with the increase of hosts on a network using TCP/IP protocols is the host count problem. an IP address of, say, 192.168.122.0, which specifies a network ID, can only fit around 254 hosts within itself because of its pre-selected network limitation. a network ID of, say, 192.168.0.0, can hold up to 65 thousand hosts. even better, 192.0.0.0 can cover up to 16.7 million networks.
so far, we seem to have learned how a host on one LAN can talk to another host on another LAN. we know how it is done. now, we learn how a computer recognizes if a data is going over to a LAN or to a WAN: the subnet mask. the subnet mask is the very trivial method of understanding how multiple networks communicate with eachother and it is as follows: a subnet mask (typically seen as 255.255.255.0 on a local network) is a numbering scheme used to compare IP addresses together to understand which method of communications to use. in a typical packet transmit scenario, there form two main methods for this action: 1: the ARP request-and-response method and 2: the subnet mask method.
1. the ARP (address resolution protocol) request-and-response method is typically used in a local network first, where the network ID (typically the first 3 octets of an IP address) match and are identical in both the nodes in transaction. when this happens, it is recognized as the nodes in a single LAN communicating with each other. ARP requests and responses are transacted and both nodes learn each other's MAC addresses to transmit data through frames.
2. the subnet mask solution: this is where routers come to play in a much more vital sense. when two computers from different LANs try to communicate with each other, their network IDs are different (example: node A IP address: 1.1.1.3 - node B IP address: 2.2.2.3). this is where subnet masks come to play: the sender node compares the recipient's IP address with its subnet masks and seees "hum, this IP address is different compared to my subnet mask. is this address in my network? no!" and it recognizes the difference, and instead of an ARP request first to the node on the other network, it sends the broadcast message to the default gateway, or the router. the router is then responsible with transmitting the given packets after the MAC address transaction. alot of the word route, right? this is definitely one of the most fascinating things in all of networking after data encapsulation.
the notation used for representing IP addresses with their subnet mask included is known as the CIDR (classless inter-domain routing), where an IP address is represented with its sum of number of 1s in its binary representation with a slash before it, as shown in the following example:
subnet mask 255.255.255.0 looks like this in its pure binary representation: 11111111 11111111 11111111 00000000
this binary representation has a total of 24 1s. say we have an IP address of 192.168.122.32: the newer, improved version is: 192.168.122.0/8 (might be more than 8 here - 122 has space left till it reaches 256 in binary)
this is done in order to represent the subnet mask and also to represent how many hosts can be available on a single network. per each single 0 in an IP address (like 192.168.122.0, 192.168.0.0, 192.0.0.0) there are different counts of how many nodes there can be on one network with that IP address, and the subnet mask comes to play in how many 0s are left and are in use. say, for 192.168.122.0, it can be represented in this fashion: 192.168.122.0/24. for 192.168.0.0: 192.168.0.0/16. note that subnet masks dont necassarily need the IP address itself to have only zeros. subnet masks may also apply to other IP addresses such as 184.222.4.24/, in which the subnet mask for this address is 255.255.255.0.
when discussing how IP addresses have been handled across the years, there seems to be an interesting scheme of "someone got hold of alot of chunks and won them for the rest of their lives". for IPv4 addreses, the IANA has handled the issue of giving out addresses to different organizations for their different networking needs. it has served this need of networking of different organizations via different classes of IP addresses. there are classes A, B, C, D, E for different IP addresses. for example, a class A IP address has room for a total of 3 octets used just for host IDs, reserving around 2^24-2 IP addresses for each host on the network. of course, class A IP addresses are mostly used only by the most corageous, most fancy organizations out there on the planet. a class B address would reserve two octets for the network ID and another two for the host IDs, reserving 2^16-2 IP addresses. a class C would hold 2^8, and classes D and E were only multicast and experimental IP addresses. so a table for classes would look something like this:
CLASS A         CLASS B         CLASS C         CLASS D         CLASS E
1.0.0.0         1.1.0.0         1.1.1.0         NO EXAM.        NO EXAM.
so per each class, there are a certain number of reserved IP addresses for hosts on the network. the higher you go from C to A, the more the number of the host counts on the network. however, it is also important to ask - what are experimental and multicast addresses used for? to understand this, we need to understand the different ways a packet is sent in first, then we can discuss the different methods.
1. broadcast: this method is used when broadcasting a message over to every available host on the network. for example: a hub broadcasts every message to every available host on the network. this is still done today in the ARP request or in other specific scenarios!
2. unicast: this is done when a computer wants to talk directly to another one in a network. every packet sent here is a unicast packet.
3. anycast: this is done when multiple computers share the same IP address - received messages are directly sent to the earliest node.
4. multicast: this is how routers talk to each other, and also how video conferencing or one-to-many methods work.
reserved or experimental IP addresses are only used in experiments. one big problem with setting up classes for network IPs has been the issue that classes didnt scale well for every organization. some organizations might need maybe 6000 addresses and using one class B address would be wasting maybe 50 thousand hosts used. this became a very big issue over time, and the solution was using CIDR and subnetting. initially, CIDR and subnetting was this weird idea of dividing a network IP class into multiple classes and making it usable by the smallest chunks of the network - now, it is the reason why the internet is still even able to use IPv4, and the crucial reason has been because of CIDR. the idea of subnetting is simply to make a network more efficient, faster bandwidth-wise, and more secure by manipulating its subnet mask. the heart of subnetting is to define how many hosts can live on the network by editing the subnet mask with it given in different numbers. for example, you may have the IP address 192.168.122.0/24 for a network. to change how many hosts can live on that IP address, you need to first convert the "24" or the subnet mask into its purely binary form, in which, as mentioned before, the 24 is simply a representations of 1s in the subnet mask that holds a 32bit value, which means /24 looks like 11111111 11111111 11111111 00000000. now you need to calculate how many hosts you need on your system: this is done, as always, by learning the number of hosts, then doing 2^x - 2 = host count, because each eight 0s leave room for 256-2 hosts. however, it is important to know that /8, /16, /24, and /32 subnet masks all represent classful masks. masks can also be numbers such as /22, or /12. when learning subnetting, the best thing to do first is to convert the subnet mask into a proper binary 32-bit long string instead of working with it in its octet form. its much more usable then. 

